In Discussion 7, we talked about the fundamental theorem of calculus for line integrals and how to find a potential function.
I also left some comments about the component test, and in particular on how it is not limited to 3-dimensional space.
The notes contain full details about the component test and include three exercises.

#horizontal-line()

I need to emphasize that if we have found a potential function for a vector field, then adding any constant `C` to that potential will also be a valid potential function.
It is a good practice to include `+C` after you solve for a potential function using either of the methods we discussed.
When the problem specifies what the potential function should be at a particular point, you can use that information to solve for `C`.

#horizontal-line()

The last exercise is Example 5 under Section 16.3 in the textbook, and it illustrates how the component test might be inconclusive when the domain of the vector field is not simply connected.